^-{        DONT - by Howard         }
^-|HT|f|CP||FP|1|at|^B@2^Z@3I|FP||AT|n normal DONT:
Double shows unspecified one-suiter and responder is forced to bid 2C. |
PG| ***** 169 ***** |


AT|
2C, 2D, 2H shows two-suiter hand (usually at least 5-4). It promises the suit bid and a higher-ranking suit. For example 2C bid means holding clubs and one of the other three suits. 2D means holding diamonds and an unspecified major and 2H means holding hearts and spades. With at least three card in bid suit responder is content to play in that suit and passes. Otherwise, bids the next higher suit or in rare cases a long suit of his own. |
PG| ***** 170 ***** |


AT|

There are two choices to show a single spades suited hand. A 2S overcall shows minimum strength. Double-then-2S over mandatory 2C bid by responder shows a strong spade suiter hand. |
PG| ***** 171 ***** |


AT|

That is normal DONT in short. As usual there are parts to normal DONT convention which occurs rather infrequently and I do not review them here.|
PG| ***** 172 ***** |


AT|

Personally, I prefer what is known as "revised DONT" which I will explain next. However, regardless of whether you play normal or revised DONT, if you have single suited spades, I think you should bid 2S, not double because 2S is very preemptive. If you double, you don't take up much room. As you recall DONT stands for "Disturb Opponents' No Trump"  and double is not very disturbing, lol. So, I like revised DONT and I always bid 2S with spades over 1N. |
PG| ***** 173 ***** |


NT||
%%%%%%%%Page
HT|e|cs|1|cp|4|
fp|1|3d|4|at|
^-{        DONT - by Howard         }
^-|HT|f|CP||FP|1|at|^B@2^Z@3I|FP||AT|n revised DONT, 2C and 2D have the same meaning as in normal DONT. (clubs and one of the other suits and diamonds and an unspecified major respectively).|
PG| ***** 174 ***** |


AT|
2H shows a single suited hand in hearts.|
PG| ***** 175 ***** |


AT|
2S shows a single suited hand in hearts. |
PG| ***** 176 ***** |


AT|
If you play revised DONT, to show hearts and spades, you double, and bid 2H over partner's forced 2C.|
PG| ***** 177 ***** |


AT|

Now, three important points:
With DONT, you cannot penalize 1N using a double, but it is rare you want to anyway.
In revised DONT, a double shows either a single suited minor or hearts and spades.
There are more occasions of single suited hearts and spades hands thus bid 2H with hearts only and 2S with a single spades suited hand.|
